Amaranthus caudatus

   [2187.jpg]
   Authority L.
   Family Magnoliopsida:Caryophyllidae:Caryophyllales:Amaranthaceae
   Synonyms Amaranthus cruentus L., Amaranthus dubius Thell., Amaranthus
   tricolor L., Amaranthus lividus L., Amaranthus viridus L., Amaranthus
   sanguineus L.
   Common names amaranths, xian, lishalisho, ferenjitef, iyaso (Galinya),
   jolili (Galinya), gagabsa (Wollamo)
   Editor
   Ecocrop code 2187

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION A herb with a main stem terminating in a large
   branched inflorescence. It may reaching a height of 2-2.5 m. Some
   varieties have red or purple leaves and long, drooping flower stalks.
   USES The leaves are used as potherbs and parts of the fresh plant are
   used as diuretic. Leaves can also be eaten as a substitute for spinach.
   Some varieties with large bright-red inflorescences are used as
   ornamentals. GROWING PERIOD Fast-growing annual. Can be harvested for
   green forages in 30-50 days. Most types mature seeds in 120-180 days,
   however in some highland regions it may require 300 days. COMMON NAMES
   Inca wheat, Quihuicha, Quinoa, Cat-tail, Love-lies-bleeding, Kiwicha,
   Inca jataco, Ataco, Ataqo, Ataku, Sankurachi, Tumbleweed, Jaguarcha,
   Millmi, Coimi, Trigo inca, Achis, Qamasa, Amaranto, Achita, Chaquilla,
   Sangorache, Borlas, Amaranto de cauda, Amaranth, Red-hot cattail, Bush
   green, Amarante caudee, Coyo. FURTHER INF Scientific synonyms: A.
   edulis, A. mantegazzianus. Found in the Andean mountains at elevations
   between 1500 and 3600 m. Near Lima, Peru it is grown at sea level.
   Adapted to low to medium humidity. It thrives best under short day
   conditions but can also flower with 12-16 hour days. Photosynthesis
   pathway C4. Yields may be up to 3-5 t/ha.

   Sources
   SOURCES (A. caudatus L.)
   Tindall H 1983 pp 36-41 [FER, TEXT, PH, TEMP, PHO]
   Roecklein J 1987 pp 34 [USE]
   Duke J 1975 pp 6 [PH, RAIN, TEMP]
   Hackett C 1982 pp 25 [FER, PHO, DEP, PH, TEXT, TEMP]
   Sims D 1993 (pers. comm.)
